result.execSummary:
The defendant Latoya N Jennings was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).
  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Latoya N Jennings in court with Attorney Jeff Allen Schwarz.  David Robles appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Matter was here for a pre-trial conference.  Defendant is now pleading.  The State orally amends each count to include PARTY TO A CRIME, 939.05.  No objection from the Defense.  The Court orders the information be amended to include PARTY TO A CRIME, 939.05 on each count.  The Court VACATES the March 23, 2016 Jury Trial date.  AS TO PLEA:  

AS TO COUNT #1:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.

AS TO COUNT #2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered case dismissed and read-in for the purposes of sentencing.

AS TO COUNT #3:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
 
Court advised defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  

The Court ordered bail to remain the same with the same conditions.  Matter set for sentencing on March 23, 2016 at 8:30am in Br. 30, Judge Conen's court.
